Chronic hepatitis B (CHB) remains a global health concern with an estimated 260 million people infected worldwide. CHB causes more than 800,000 deaths a year due to HBV‚Äêrelated complications such as cirrhosis and HCC.(
1
) In the absence of novel treatment strategies, it is projected that new cases of CHB will rise to three million per year by 2030.(
2
) Current approved therapies include long‚Äêterm antiviral suppression with nucleos(t)ide analogues and pegylated interferon‚ÄêŒ± (IFN‚ÄêŒ±). These treatments reduce viremia and improve patient outcomes but are rarely curative.(
3
) As a consequence, there is a pressing need for novel immunotherapeutic strategies to supplement existing direct‚Äêacting antivirals to achieve durable immune control.

Control of HBV is dependent on the coordinated action of both innate and adaptive immunity.(
4
) A major obstacle to HBV clearance in CHB is a dysfunctional adaptive response, characterized by a profound state of immune exhaustion and HBV‚Äêspecific T‚Äêcell depletion.(
5, 6
) The mechanism by which this dysfunction occurs is multifaceted, but likely driven by a combination of ongoing high‚Äêdose antigenic stimulation and the tolerogenic liver environment. Moreover, while the natural killer (NK) cell compartment can exert direct and indirect antiviral activity, they may also restrict effective antiviral immunity by deleting apoptosis‚Äêprone HBV‚Äêspecific T cells. Specifically, NK cells in the HBV‚Äêinfected liver up‚Äêregulate the death‚Äêligand TNF‚Äêrelated apoptosis‚Äêinducing ligand (TRAIL), enabling them to engage with and eliminate T cells expressing the reciprocal receptor, TRAIL‚Äêreceptor 2 (TRAIL‚ÄêR2).(
7, 8
) Another mechanism contributing to the suppression of HBV immunity is the expansion of arginase+ polymorphonuclear myeloid‚Äêderived suppressor cells (PMN‚ÄêMDSCs), which deplete key nutrients required by T cells for proliferation and function.(
9
)

One therapeutic approach in clinical development for CHB is to engage innate immune receptors such as toll‚Äêlike receptors (TLRs), which can exert both direct and indirect effects on the antiviral T‚Äêcell and B‚Äêcell response. A previous therapeutic strategy attempted to harness TLR7 signaling using the agonist GS‚Äê9620 (vesatolimod). GS‚Äê9620 induced sustained antiviral responses in animal models,(
10, 11
) but failed to show therapeutic efficacy in patients with CHB.(
12, 13
)

More recently, attention has turned to TLR8 activation due to its anticipated ability to stimulate host immunity through the induction of pro‚Äêinflammatory and immunomodulatory cytokines. Human TLR8 is predominantly expressed on the endosomal membrane of monocytes, macrophages, conventional dendritic cells (cDCs), and CD4+ regulatory T cells (TREG), and allows cells to respond to infection through detection of viral single‚Äêstranded RNA.(
14, 15, 16
) GS‚Äê9688 (selgantolimod) is an oral selective small‚Äêmolecule agonist of TLR8 in development for CHB. In vitro studies have demonstrated that cytokines induced in human peripheral blood mononuclear cells (PBMCs) by GS‚Äê9688 reduce viral parameters in HBV‚Äêinfected primary human hepatocytes.(
17
) Furthermore, GS‚Äê9688 treatment was well tolerated and induced a sustained antiviral response in a subset of woodchuck hepatitis virus‚Äìinfected woodchucks.(
18
) Although these preclinical studies provide some insight into the antiviral efficacy of GS‚Äê9688, they did not provide insight into the mode of action of GS‚Äê9688 on human immune cells.

sec.p:
GS‚Äê9688 (selgantolimod) is a small‚Äêmolecule TLR8 agonist manufactured by Gilead Sciences Inc. (Foster City, CA).(
17
) Concentrations used are denoted in the figures/figure legends.

To investigate the therapeutic potential of the TLR8 agonist GS‚Äê9688, we first assessed its in vitro activity and potency using human PBMCs isolated from 10 healthy controls. PBMCs were stimulated with GS‚Äê9688, and cell culture supernatants were evaluated by Luminex array (Fig. 1A). Among the cytokines tested, GS‚Äê9688 induced the immunomodulatory cytokine IL‚Äê12p40, in addition to the antiviral cytokines IL‚Äê6, TNF‚ÄêŒ±, and interferon‚Äêg (IFN‚ÄêŒ≥) (Fig. 1B and Supporting Fig. S1A). GS‚Äê9688‚Äêdependent cytokine induction occurred in a dose‚Äêdependent manner, with a mean MEC and EC50 of 29/217¬†nM, 54/326¬†nM, and 55/267¬†nM for IL‚Äê12p40, TNF‚ÄêŒ± and IFN‚ÄêŒ≥, respectively (Fig. 1C and Supporting Fig. S1A). Additionally, GS‚Äê9688 induced the production of the pro‚Äêinflammatory cytokines IL‚Äê1Œ±, IL‚Äê1Œ≤, and the anti‚Äêinflammatory mediator IL‚Äê1RA (Fig. 1B,C and Supporting Fig. S1A). Conversely, GS‚Äê9688 induced little to no IFN‚ÄêŒ±, a prototypical cytokine predominantly produced following engagement of TLR7,(
19, 20
) consistent with its selectivity for human TLR8(
17
) (Fig. 1B,C and Supporting Fig. S1A). Importantly, there was no significant difference in response in PBMCs from 10 age‚Äêmatched patients with CHB, with comparable MEC, EC50, and Emax for all cytokines tested (Fig. 1C and Supporting Fig. S1A).

To investigate the cellular source of relevant immunomodulatory cytokines, we examined the effect of GS‚Äê9688 on circulating myeloid cells. Human TLR8 is expressed primarily by cDCs and mononuclear phagocytes (MNPs), but is absent on plasmacytoid dendritic cells (pDCs).(
14, 15, 16
) Short‚Äêterm stimulation of PBMCs with GS‚Äê9688 increased production of IL‚Äê12p40 by Lin1‚àíHLA‚ÄêDR+CD123‚àíCD11c+ cDCs, in a dose‚Äêdependent manner (Fig. 1D). Likewise, TNF‚ÄêŒ± was produced by cDCs and Lin1+CD14+ MNPs in response to GS‚Äê9688 (Fig. 1E). The cDCs, pDCs, and MNPs produced minimal IFN‚ÄêŒ± when treated with GS‚Äê9688, consistent with selective activation of TLR8 by GS‚Äê9688 (Supporting Fig. S1B). The activation and induction of immunomodulatory cytokines was supported by augmented expression of the activation marker CD40 on both cDCs and MNPs (Supporting Fig. S1C). Collectively, these data demonstrate that GS‚Äê9688 activates cDCs and MNPs and is a potent inducer of the immunomodulatory cytokines IL‚Äê12 and TNF‚ÄêŒ± in vitro.

CD8+ T cells are critical for the control of HBV infection, mediated in part through their capacity for noncytolytic inhibition of HBV replication by the secretion of antiviral cytokines.(
21, 22, 23
) It is increasingly recognized that local cytokine environments can shape adaptive immune responses. Therefore, we tested the capacity of the cytokines induced by GS‚Äê9688 to indirectly modulate the frequency of functional HBV‚Äêspecific CD8+ T cells in response to HBV‚ÄêOLP using PBMCs isolated from patients with CHB (clinical parameters at the time of sampling in Supporting Table S1 and gating strategy in Supporting Fig. S2A). In 13 of 28 patients examined, treatment with GS‚Äê9688 increased the frequency of CD8+ T cells producing the antiviral cytokine IFN‚ÄêŒ≥ in response to HBcAg (Fig. 2A,B). A similar proportion of patients showed no increase in the number of IFN‚ÄêŒ≥+ HBV‚Äêspecific CD8+ T cells following stimulation with GS‚Äê9688 (Fig. 2B). Interestingly, de novo IFN‚ÄêŒ≥ responses induced by GS‚Äê9688 were detected in 3 patients who lacked a detectable HBV‚Äêspecific response to HBV‚Äêcore OLP stimulation alone. Similarly, when using a panel of HLA‚Äêrestricted peptide multimers (Supporting Table S2) to detect HBV‚Äêspecific CD8+ T cells after peptide expansion, the response to GS‚Äê9688 was heterogenous. Here, 9 of 23 patients showed a substantial increase in the proportion of detectable HBV‚Äêspecific CD8+ T cells (Fig. 2C). Notably, the mean fluorescence intensity (MFI) of IFN‚ÄêŒ≥ from the HBV‚Äêspecific IFN‚ÄêŒ≥+ CD8+ T‚Äêcell pool showed a modest increase, suggesting a greater production of this antiviral cytokine per cell in response to HBV‚Äêcore OLP in the presence of GS‚Äê9688 (Fig. 2D). Furthermore, when assessing the frequency of polyfunctional CD8+ T cells, we observed an increase in the proportion of CD8+ T cells producing both IFN‚ÄêŒ≥ and TNF‚ÄêŒ± in 10 patients (36%; Fig. 2E). In contrast, the percentage of CD8+ T cells degranulating in response to HBV‚Äêcore OLP only increased in 3 (16%) patients following treatment with GS‚Äê9688 (Supporting Fig. S2B). Taken together, these data support the potential of GS‚Äê9688 to enhance the noncytolytic effector function of pre‚Äêexisting endogenous HBV‚Äêspecific CD8+ T cells, and to increase the frequency of antiviral T cells in a subset of patients.

Innate effector cells such as NK cells play a dual role in the setting of viral infection. Although these immune mediators can exert antiviral activity by direct or indirect effects (e.g., through modulation of T‚Äêcell responses), emerging data underscore mechanisms by which they limit antiviral responses through the inhibition or killing of antigen‚Äêspecific T cells. In CHB, NK cells can also become defective in their capacity to produce IFN‚ÄêŒ≥ and TNF‚ÄêŒ±, resulting in an inability to effectively exert noncytolytic activity in the HBV‚Äêinfected liver.(
24, 25
)

To address the functional impact of GS‚Äê9688 on NK cells in vitro, we determined the activation status of the global NK cell population in response to GS‚Äê9688 treatment of PBMCs from healthy controls and patients with CHB. GS‚Äê9688 activated NK cells in a dose‚Äêdependent manner, increasing the expression of the activation markers CD69, HLA‚ÄêDR, and CD38 (gating strategy; Supporting Fig. S3A and Fig. 3A). Activation was evident on both the immature cytokine producing CD56bright population, which has been described to be preferentially enriched in the liver,(
26
) and the cytotoxic, more mature CD56dim subset (Supporting Fig. S3B,C). In line with their activation, treatment with GS‚Äê9688 augmented the noncytolytic effector function of NK cells, confirmed by an increased production of TNF‚ÄêŒ± and IFN‚ÄêŒ≥ (Fig. 3B). As expected, the increase in cytokine production driven by GS‚Äê9688 was largely attributable to the CD56bright population (Supporting Fig. S3D). NK cells do not express TLR8 but can be activated by TLR8 agonists through the production of IL‚Äê12 and IL‚Äê18.(
27
) Consistent with these data, neutralization of IL‚Äê12/IL‚Äê18 abrogated the IFN‚ÄêŒ≥ production seen in response to GS‚Äê9688 treatment in the 6 individuals tested, at all concentrations of GS‚Äê9688 (Fig. 3B). This finding supports a role for GS‚Äê9688‚Äêinduced cytokines in promoting NK‚Äêcell antiviral function.

Although IFN‚ÄêŒ≥ production by NK cells can promote antiviral T‚Äêcell responses and inhibit viral replication in hepatocytes, additional anti‚ÄêHBV activity of NK cells is attributable to their ability to directly eliminate infected hepatocytes.(
25
) In line with this, GS‚Äê9688 enhanced the cytolytic capacity of NK cells, as indicated by increased expression of perforin and granzyme B (Fig. 3C) and the propensity for degranulation, as denoted by CD107a mobilization (Fig. 3D). Moreover, GS‚Äê9688‚Äêtreated, purified NK cells also increased lysis of the HepG2 hepatoma cell line (Fig. 3E). Collectively, these data demonstrate that GS‚Äê9688 enhances both the noncytolytic and cytolytic effector functions of NK cells in vitro.

Although a role for MAITs (non‚Äêclassical T cells characterized by expression of the invariant chain VŒ±7.2) in CHB remains unclear, they are highly enriched in the liver and are potent producers of IFN‚ÄêŒ≥ in response to TLR8 agonism.(
28
) GS‚Äê9688 activated MAITs in PBMCs, increasing the expression of IFN‚ÄêŒ≥ and granzyme B (Supporting Fig. S4A‚ÄêC). Analogous to NK cells, this increase in the noncytolytic and cytolytic potential of MAITs by GS‚Äê9688 was IL‚Äê12/IL‚Äê18‚Äêdependent in 2 healthy controls (Supporting Fig. S4B,C).

In CHB, NK cells can also mediate negative regulatory effects by up‚Äêregulating death ligands such as TRAIL to kill HBV‚Äêspecific T cells selectively expressing TRAIL‚ÄêR2.(
7, 8
) Furthermore, TRAIL‚Äêexpressing NK cells have the potential to directly kill hepatocytes.(
7
) GS‚Äê9688 treatment induced a significant increase in TRAIL‚Äêexpressing NK cells (Fig. 3F), which was most evident on the CD56bright subset (Fig. 3F and Supporting Fig. S3E).

Follicular helper CD4+ T cells (TFH) play a key role in promoting adaptive immunity through the generation of long‚Äêlived plasma cells.(
29, 30
) In contrast, CD4+ TREG cells are potent immunosuppressors able to down‚Äêregulate adaptive immunity, with previous studies reporting increases in the proportion of circulating and liver‚Äêresident TREG in patients, that actively inhibit the antiviral response and contributes to chronicity in CHB.(
31
) Importantly, recent studies have highlighted the capacity of TLR8 agonists to both reduce the suppressive capacity of TREG in a model of antitumor immunity(
15
) and enhance TFH differentiation.(
32
) Thus, GS‚Äê9688 was examined for its effect on the frequency and phenotype of circulating TFH (cTFH) and TREG cells by quantifying their proportions in PBMCs isolated from patients with CHB or healthy controls (TREG: CD4+CD25hiCD127loFOXP3+; cTFH: CD4+CXCR5+PD‚Äê1+; gating strategy found in Supporting Fig. S5A) after in vitro culture.

Although the overall proportion of CD4+ T cells remained unchanged (Supporting Fig. S5B), there was an increase in the frequency of cTFH in response to GS‚Äê9688 at all doses tested (Fig. 4A). Furthermore, GS‚Äê9688 altered the phenotype of cTFH by increasing the expression of inducible T‚Äêcell co‚Äêstimulator (ICOS), a marker for TFH differentiation and function(
33
) (Fig. 4B). Conversely, treatment with GS‚Äê9688 induced a dose‚Äêdependent decrease in the frequency of circulating TREG (Fig. 4C). Despite reducing the frequency of TREG, GS‚Äê9688 had little impact on the immunosuppressive potential of the remaining TREG population on the basis of unaltered expression of the negative regulator, cytotoxic T‚Äêlymphocyte‚Äêassociated protein 4 (CTLA4; Fig. 4D) and CD39, the rate‚Äêlimiting enzyme in the generation of immunosuppressive adenosine (Fig. 4E). Although the potential for suppression by the remaining TREG population was unaffected by GS‚Äê9688, the ability of GS‚Äê9688 to decrease the frequency of TREG suggests that it may act to reduce the overall capacity of TREG to limit HBV‚Äêspecific T‚Äêcell responses in vivo.

MDSCs are immature myeloid progenitors that exert potent immune regulation through the manipulation of nutrient availability and expression of inhibitory ligands like programmed death‚Äêligand 1 (PD‚ÄêL1).(
34
) The MDSC compartment consists of two populations, polymorphonuclear MDSCs (PMN‚ÄêMDSCs) and monocytic MDSCs (M‚ÄêMDSCs).(
34
) Arginase‚ÄêI expressing PMN‚ÄêMDSCs accumulate in patients with CHB, where they limit the proliferation and function of bystander and HBV‚Äêspecific T cells.(
9
) Different TLR8 agonists were recently shown to reduce M‚ÄêMDSC frequencies in vitro by selectively inducing their apoptosis and limiting their immunosuppressive activity.(
35, 36
) Consequently, we assessed the capacity of GS‚Äê9688 to modulate the frequency and functionality of MDSC.

GS‚Äê9688 induced MDSC activation, as determined by increased expression of CD80 (Fig. 5B) and altered the immunosuppressive potential of both subsets in vitro. Short‚Äêterm GS‚Äê9688 exposure decreased expression of intracellular arginase‚ÄêI in PMN‚ÄêMDSCs, while simultaneously increasing its expression in M‚ÄêMDSCs, albeit to a much lower level than the PMN‚ÄêMDSCs (Fig. 5C). Expression of CD63, a measure of azurophilic granule mobilization to the cell surface, remained unchanged on PMN‚ÄêMDSCs but dramatically increased on M‚ÄêMDSCs (Fig. 5D). These data are suggestive of active degranulation of MDSC in vitro triggered by GS‚Äê9688, supported by an increased release of extracellular arginase‚ÄêI into the culture media (Fig. 5E). In addition, we observed an increase in expression of the negative regulators galectin‚Äê9 (on both subsets of MDSCs) and PD‚ÄêL1 (on the remaining M‚ÄêMDSCs), which could conceivably result in enhanced suppression of T‚Äêcell immunoglobulin and mucin domain containing‚Äê3 (Tim‚Äê3)‚Äêexpressing or programmed cell death protein 1 (PD‚Äê1)‚Äêexpressing HBV‚Äêspecific T cells(
6, 37
) (Fig. 5F,G).

GS‚Äê9688 is a potent TLR8 agonist in development for the treatment of CHB. A recent study in the woodchuck model of CHB revealed that a short, finite period of dosing with GS‚Äê9688 is well tolerated and able to induce a sustained antiviral response.(
18
) Here we evaluated the immunomodulatory effect of GS‚Äê9688 on various immune cells in vitro using human PBMCs to understand its therapeutic potential for CHB.

Initial experiments confirmed GS‚Äê9688 selectivity for TLR8, revealing the potent induction of immunomodulatory cytokines, such as IL‚Äê12, by cDCs and MNPs, which was preserved in PBMCs from patients with CHB. In interrogating the effects on correlates of immune protection, we showed that GS‚Äê9688 enhanced the frequency of HBV‚Äêspecific CD8+ T cells in a subset of patients. In vitro treatment with GS‚Äê9688 boosted the production of antiviral cytokines, but not cytotoxicity, of HBV‚Äêspecific CD8+ T cells. The potential for GS‚Äê9688 to enhance cellular mediators with antiviral potential in CHB was further evidenced by increased activation, improved cytolytic and noncytolytic effector function of NK cells, and MAITs. In the HBV‚Äêinfected liver, where NK cells are greatly enriched and where the virus‚Äêspecific T‚Äêcell response is limited, it is possible that GS‚Äê9688‚Äêactivated NK cells could perform a significant antiviral role through secretion of cytokines, and enhanced killing of infected hepatocytes. In line with other TLR8 agonists, we confirmed that the increase in antiviral activity by these effectors was driven by induction of IL‚Äê12/IL‚Äê18. IL‚Äê12 has the potential to reverse mitochondrial defects of exhausted HBV‚Äêspecific CD8+ T cells, allowing for more efficient bioenergetics and enhanced antiviral functionality.(
38, 39, 40
) Importantly, the therapeutic benefit of IL‚Äê12 has been demonstrated in HBV transgenic mice, the woodchuck model of CHB, and in early clinical trials in patients with CHB.(
41, 42, 43, 44
)

Although promising, it is important to note that GS‚Äê9688 did not induce an effective HBV‚Äêspecific CD8+ T‚Äêcell response in PBMCs from all patients, which is typical of many immunotherapeutic strategies in development for CHB using diverse patient cohorts.(
6, 37, 45
) This is reminiscent of the antiviral response to GS‚Äê9688 in the woodchuck model of CHB, in which only half the animals treated with 3¬†mg/kg GS‚Äê9688 had a sustained reduction in viral parameters.(
18
) Consistent with the woodchuck study, the response of patient HBV‚Äêspecific CD8+ T cells in vitro was not associated with age, sex, extent of liver inflammation, or viral load. However, the magnitude of the in vitro response was associated with a low‚Äêbaseline HBsAg titer (<2,000¬†IU/mL). To elucidate the potential differences in responders and non‚Äêresponders, it is important to consider the contribution of potent immunoregulatory leukocytes implicated in suppressing T‚Äêcell immunity. In this study we show increased expression of the death ligand TRAIL on NK cells, particularly on the CD56bright subset driven by GS‚Äê9688, which may further eliminate the already depleted pool of HBV‚Äêspecific T cells within the infected liver.(
8
) Conversely, these TRAIL+NK cells may act as antifibrotic mediators in CHB, killing activated hepatic stellate cells in a TRAIL‚Äêdependent manner or by producing hepatoprotective cytokines.(
46
)

A notable finding of this study was GS‚Äê9688 modulation of immunosuppressive cells. GS‚Äê9688 reduced the frequency of TREG, potent immunosuppressors implicated in CHB.(
31
) Intriguingly, the decline in TREG numbers was associated with a corresponding expansion and activation of cTFH. The observed GS‚Äê9688‚Äêdriven increase in ICOS expression on cTFH is significant, as ICOS is critical for IL‚Äê21 production and the subsequent delivery of improved T‚Äêcell help.(
47, 48
) Although not studied here, we hypothesize that such an increase in cTFH and TFH‚Äêassociated cytokines will improve immune control in CHB by modulating the frequency of memory B cells and the production of affinity‚Äêmatured class‚Äêswitched antibodies. Whether this decrease in TREG and expansion and activation of cTFH is sufficient to overcome the observed B‚Äêcell dysfunction characteristic of patients with CHB will require further study.(
49, 50
)

Various other mechanisms have been identified that play a role in immune dysfunction in CHB, including the increased activity of MDSCs. Consistent with the literature,(
35, 36
) we demonstrate the capacity of GS‚Äê9688 to decrease the frequency of M‚ÄêMDSCs in vitro. However, this decrease was linked to an initial burst of arginase‚ÄêI release from PMN‚ÄêMDSCs, which may transiently limit the availability of the conditionally essential amino acid L‚Äêarginine, acting as a crucial T‚Äêcell rheostat.(
9
) Of further significance is the capacity of GS‚Äê9688 to induce expression of PD‚ÄêL1 and galectin‚Äê9 on the remaining MDSCs, which could limit HBV‚Äêspecific CD8+ T cells expressing high levels of PD‚Äê1 and Tim‚Äê3.(
6, 37
) Intrahepatic PD‚ÄêL1 and galectin‚Äê9 levels are increased in viral hepatitis, and our data suggest that they may be further enhanced by TLR8‚Äêinduced IFN‚ÄêŒ≥.(
37, 51
) Collectively, these data raise the possibility that combination with checkpoint blockade may improve the antiviral response to GS‚Äê9688 treatment.

GS‚Äê9688 has good absorption and high first‚Äêpass hepatic clearance, to limit systemic immune activation.(
17
) After oral administration of GS‚Äê9688, intestinal absorption is expected to induce TLR8 activation in the gut and liver, where the immune composition is markedly different.(
26, 52, 53, 54
) It is likely that the secretion of immune mediators from the gut into the portal vein will in turn stimulate cells in the liver. Given the fact that the liver harbors a population of transcriptionally distant liver‚Äêresident NK cells(
26
) and memory CD8+ T cells(
53, 54
) future studies will need to focus on characterizing the intrahepatic immune response to GS‚Äê9688.

Although the therapeutic efficacy of GS‚Äê9688 in combination with nucleos(t)ide treatment remains to be fully evaluated in patients with CHB, it was shown to be safe and generally well‚Äêtolerated in a phase 2 placebo‚Äêcontrolled study in virally suppressed patients, with a subset achieving HBsAg and/or HBeAg loss.(
55
) While phase 2 studies are ongoing (ClinicalTrials.gov NCT03491553/NCT03615066), our work provides important insights into the immunomodulatory effects of GS‚Äê9688 and has important implications for the rational design of combination studies with other immunomodulatory agents. Our data also raise the possibility that in vitro profiling of PBMC responses to GS‚Äê9688 in patients with CHB may have utility for predicting therapeutic efficacy in patients.
